WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.640
all about India, by Philippa-Tracy, chapter 1, ancient and

00:05.640 --> 00:06.620
medieval history.

00:08.120 --> 00:12.460
Greetings! I am the spirit of Ashukha the Great. In

00:12.460 --> 00:14.660
the third century B.C., I ruled

00:14.660 --> 00:19.620
for almost four decades over the Morian Empire, the largest

00:19.620 --> 00:22.980
empire in India. My emblem, the

00:22.980 --> 00:26.100
Ashukha chakra wheel, is in the center of the Indian

00:26.100 --> 00:28.300
flag and it symbolizes movement,

00:28.300 --> 00:33.220
like a wheel, India is always in motion, constantly changing

00:33.220 --> 00:34.700
and making progress.

00:36.120 --> 00:39.380
The Indian subcontinent got its name from the word Indus,

00:39.780 --> 00:41.040
because its first civilization,

00:41.920 --> 00:46.140
the Indus Valley civilization, lived on the Indus River, in

00:46.140 --> 00:47.620
today's Pakistan and

00:47.620 --> 00:51.780
Northwest India. Being Emperor of India was not an easy

00:51.780 --> 00:53.740
job, as the country was so

00:53.740 --> 00:58.700
enormous, about 13 times the size of the UK. For

00:58.700 --> 01:00.880
centuries, India was divided into

01:00.880 --> 01:04.420
lots of small kingdoms, each governed by its own ruler.

01:05.220 --> 01:06.900
This led to political problems,

01:07.400 --> 01:10.240
as the rulers didn't always see things the same way.

01:10.920 --> 01:13.380
With so many rulers governing at the same time,

01:13.740 --> 01:16.400
it was very difficult for the emperor to keep universal

01:16.400 --> 01:18.180
power over his empire.

01:19.060 --> 01:24.080
Empires rose and empires fell, some lasted decades or centuries,

01:24.760 --> 01:25.600
while others quickly

01:25.600 --> 01:30.760
disintegrated because they had weak rulers. All these rulers changed

01:30.760 --> 01:32.820
the face of India in some way,

01:33.560 --> 01:36.960
but only one of them succeeded in uniting India's kingdoms

01:36.960 --> 01:38.320
into one state.

01:39.280 --> 01:42.960
His name was Chandra Gupta Moria, and he was the

01:42.960 --> 01:45.820
powerful and strong warrior who founded the

01:45.820 --> 01:50.200
Morian dynasty. He ruled as the first Morian emperor of

01:50.200 --> 01:54.820
India from 321 to 297 BC.

01:55.960 --> 02:00.280
By the way, he was also my grandfather. When Chandra

02:00.280 --> 02:02.440
Gupta died, my father,

02:02.780 --> 02:08.920
Bin Dusara, followed him and ruled from 297 to 272

02:08.920 --> 02:14.640
or 3 BC. He had 16 wives and many children,

02:14.640 --> 02:17.360
which meant there was a lot of competition for the

02:17.360 --> 02:20.680
throne. After his death, the fighting for

02:20.680 --> 02:24.740
the throne continued for four long years until I finally

02:24.740 --> 02:27.860
got the most support. I took my father's

02:27.860 --> 02:33.460
place as emperor in 268 BC and ruled until 232

02:33.460 --> 02:37.860
BC, expanding India's territories even more.

02:38.780 --> 02:42.400
I believed in Buddhism and dedicated my life to spreading

02:42.400 --> 02:44.060
this religion in my country.

02:44.640 --> 02:47.880
I was considered one of the most powerful emperors of

02:47.880 --> 02:50.240
the Indian subcontinent in ancient times,

02:50.860 --> 02:54.020
and mine was one of the most glorious and prosperous

02:54.020 --> 02:56.120
periods in Indian history.

02:57.000 --> 03:00.500
Maybe that's why my emblem appears on the modern Indian

03:00.500 --> 03:00.920
flag.

03:02.100 --> 03:07.780
When I died in 232 BC, my people were inconsolable.

03:08.640 --> 03:14.620
According to legend,

03:14.620 --> 03:19.460
people saw this as a sign of my greatness. Unfortunately,

03:19.940 --> 03:21.740
all good things come to an end,

03:22.380 --> 03:25.260
and the Morian Empire fell when the last of the

03:25.260 --> 03:28.860
Morian rulers was killed in 185 BC.

03:30.100 --> 03:33.700
However, the end of one era marks the beginning of

03:33.700 --> 03:36.260
another, and there were many other emperors,

03:36.820 --> 03:39.340
not as great as my grandfather and I if I

03:39.340 --> 03:42.900
may say so, but who were also admirable and good

03:42.900 --> 03:43.320
for the

03:43.320 --> 03:49.300
country? Between the fourth and sixth centuries AD, India experienced

03:49.300 --> 03:50.480
its golden age,

03:50.940 --> 03:57.080
with powerful rulers like Chandragupta I and Chandragupta II. This

03:57.080 --> 03:58.040
was a time of many

03:58.040 --> 04:03.480
achievements in the fields of engineering, arts, science, technology and

04:03.480 --> 04:03.780
religion.

04:04.820 --> 04:08.840
During this period, chess was invented, and a monetary system

04:08.840 --> 04:10.540
was used for the first time.

04:11.240 --> 04:16.360
Later, impressive temples were built. Already in the 11th century

04:16.360 --> 04:18.480
AD, builders managed to move

04:18.480 --> 04:22.360
an 82,000 kg stone to the top of a

04:22.360 --> 04:26.800
temple. How did they do that amazing thing? We still

04:26.800 --> 04:27.480
don't know.

04:28.740 --> 04:33.380
Archaeological evidence shows that water conservation for irrigation was another

04:33.380 --> 04:37.920
important achievement of ancient India. Can you believe that people

04:37.920 --> 04:39.260
still use this ancient

04:39.260 --> 04:44.200
system today? Now let's move on to another important empire.

04:45.380 --> 04:47.280
Have you ever wondered why so many

04:47.280 --> 04:52.220
Indians are also Muslims? The first Muslims arrived in India

04:52.220 --> 04:54.640
in the 8th century and slowly

04:54.640 --> 04:59.680
began to conquer territory. Muslim invaders founded the Mughal Empire

04:59.680 --> 05:09.240
in 1526. They were a strong

05:09.800 --> 05:14.420
during the reign of Akbar the Great. The Mughals also

05:14.420 --> 05:17.300
built impressive monuments like the Taj Mahal

05:17.300 --> 05:21.340
and the Red Fort and introduced an effective tax collection

05:21.340 --> 05:24.080
system. Although they were Muslims,

05:24.840 --> 05:28.160
they were influenced by the Hindus and respected their culture.

05:30.280 --> 05:30.280
Unfortunately,

05:30.740 --> 05:34.460
not all the Mughal emperors were like Akbar. Many of

05:34.460 --> 05:37.160
them were useless rulers who killed their own

05:37.160 --> 05:42.680
families to win the throne. Orangzeb, the sixth emperor of

05:42.680 --> 05:43.460
the Mughal Empire,

05:43.560 --> 05:47.940
was particularly cruel. He imprisoned his father and ordered his

05:47.940 --> 05:49.040
servants to cut off

05:49.040 --> 05:52.220
his elder brother's head, which he sent to his father

05:52.220 --> 05:55.080
in a basket. Despite his cruelty,

05:55.680 --> 05:58.560
Orangzeb was the last of the great emperors of the

05:58.560 --> 06:01.140
Mughal dynasty. By the time he died,

06:01.140 --> 06:08.460
after ruling for almost 49 years, 1658-1707, the Mughal

06:08.460 --> 06:10.740
Empire was already disintegrating.

06:11.460 --> 06:14.020
His death marked the end of an era and the

06:14.020 --> 06:16.920
beginning of the modern or colonial period.

06:17.960 --> 06:21.220
There were other emperors after him, but the wars of

06:21.220 --> 06:22.960
succession and bad administration

06:23.640 --> 06:26.740
led to the collapse of the Mughal Empire in the

06:26.740 --> 06:28.140
mid-18th century.

06:28.140 --> 06:32.440
I would love to share more of India's fascinating ancient

06:32.440 --> 06:34.120
and medieval history with you,

06:34.520 --> 06:37.420
but I must continue in my search for self-knowledge,

06:37.940 --> 06:39.060
so I'm leaving now.

06:39.820 --> 06:42.320
It's time for you to learn about India's modern history,

06:43.160 --> 06:45.000
Mahatma Gandhi and India's

06:45.000 --> 06:49.600
fight for independence. CHAPTER II THE ROAD TO INDIPENDANCE

06:50.360 --> 06:54.480
Colonial rule In the 1600s in Europe,

06:54.480 --> 06:59.240
tea and spices were in high demand. India produced these,

06:59.680 --> 07:03.320
so Queen Elizabeth I of England sent merchants to start

07:03.320 --> 07:05.000
a trading company in India,

07:05.800 --> 07:11.200
the British East India Company, EIC. It controlled all trade

07:11.200 --> 07:12.660
between England and Asia.

07:13.500 --> 07:17.340
For more than 100 years, the company traded mostly with

07:17.340 --> 07:19.420
India buying cheap cotton cloth,

07:19.420 --> 07:23.780
silk, sugar and spices, which they sold for a lot

07:23.780 --> 07:24.220
of money.

07:25.260 --> 07:28.660
The Mughal emperors permitted the British to build factories in

07:28.660 --> 07:28.900
Bombay,

07:29.700 --> 07:33.640
Madras and Calcutta, and as more and more British traders

07:33.640 --> 07:35.160
went to live near the factories,

07:35.780 --> 07:41.880
these areas developed into colonies. THE MARATAS AND GROWING BRITISH

07:41.880 --> 07:42.420
INFLUENCE

07:43.340 --> 07:46.920
The Maratas were Hindu warriors who were at war with

07:46.920 --> 07:49.020
the Mughals. They had existed

07:49.020 --> 07:53.440
since the 14th century, but as the Mughal Empire continued

07:53.440 --> 07:54.120
to decline,

07:54.560 --> 07:57.940
they started to become more powerful and they established their

07:57.940 --> 08:01.320
own Maratha Empire in 1674.

08:02.220 --> 08:05.960
After the last Mughal Emperor with any real power died

08:05.960 --> 08:09.880
in 1748, the Maratas easily took

08:09.880 --> 08:14.260
control of most of northern India. However, they didn't have

08:14.260 --> 08:16.580
an emperor. They had several

08:16.580 --> 08:22.540
Pishwas, Prime Ministers governing different areas. This weakened the power

08:22.540 --> 08:23.640
of the Maratha Empire,

08:24.260 --> 08:27.500
making it easier for the growing British population to take

08:27.500 --> 08:27.960
control.

08:29.020 --> 08:31.800
There were many problems between the British and the Governor

08:31.800 --> 08:32.260
of Bengal,

08:33.520 --> 08:37.440
Siraj Al-Dula, who had taken Calcutta from the British.

08:38.100 --> 08:39.760
The tension led to the Battle

08:39.760 --> 08:45.460
of Plasi in 1757. The British defeated Siraj Al-Dula's

08:45.460 --> 08:47.760
army and then bribed their candidate

08:47.760 --> 08:52.820
Mia Yafur to become the Governor of Bengal. This victory

08:52.820 --> 08:54.840
in the Battle of Plasi led to

08:54.840 --> 08:58.340
the expanding of British rule in India, which lasted for

08:58.340 --> 08:59.760
almost 200 years.

09:01.020 --> 09:04.980
In 1775, there was a fight for power among the

09:04.980 --> 09:07.860
Pishwas, and the British East Indian Company

09:07.860 --> 09:12.600
was implicated. This British interference in the affairs of the

09:12.600 --> 09:15.020
Maratas led to the first of three

09:15.020 --> 09:20.280
Anglo-Maratha Wars. In the Third War, in 1818, the

09:20.280 --> 09:22.140
British defeated the Maratas.

09:22.900 --> 09:26.840
Now British rule was even stronger, and they influenced daily

09:26.840 --> 09:27.820
life in India.

09:28.540 --> 09:32.480
Because the British needed more money, taxes and territories to

09:32.480 --> 09:33.880
support their large armies,

09:33.880 --> 09:38.780
they continued to fight. They conquered territory after territory, and

09:38.780 --> 09:39.840
their empire grew.

09:40.760 --> 09:44.360
The Indian people soon got tired of British rulers, who

09:44.360 --> 09:45.880
had no respect for their religions,

09:46.420 --> 09:49.960
and who tried to change some of their traditions. In

09:49.960 --> 09:53.940
1857, the British officers went one step too

09:53.940 --> 09:58.640
far by ordering Indian soldiers to load ammunition that had

09:58.640 --> 10:00.260
cow and pig fat on it,

10:00.700 --> 10:03.620
even though they knew that cows are holy to Hindus

10:03.620 --> 10:05.960
and pigs are repulsive to Muslims.

10:07.100 --> 10:10.900
Many people condemned the East India Company for allowing this

10:10.900 --> 10:11.400
to happen,

10:12.000 --> 10:14.700
and it led to the Indian Mutiny, which took the

10:14.700 --> 10:17.300
lives of hundreds of thousands of soldiers.

10:18.380 --> 10:22.120
At this point, Queen Victoria finally realised that a trading

10:22.120 --> 10:24.280
company couldn't rule an empire,

10:24.820 --> 10:28.840
and in 1858, she made India part of the British

10:28.840 --> 10:29.220
Empire.

10:30.680 --> 10:33.320
British rule and the struggle for freedom.

10:34.560 --> 10:39.420
In 1905, the British government adopted a divide and rule

10:39.420 --> 10:41.980
policy to stop Indians from uniting

10:41.980 --> 10:47.180
against British rule in India. They divided Bengal into West

10:47.180 --> 10:47.480
Bengal,

10:48.360 --> 10:53.320
mainly Hindu, and East Bengal, mainly Muslim. Because if the

10:53.320 --> 10:54.920
Hindus and Muslims were united,

10:55.560 --> 10:58.300
they would have too much power and could challenge British

10:58.300 --> 10:59.480
control over India.

10:59.480 --> 11:02.560
The jewel in the crown of the British Empire.

11:03.820 --> 11:08.620
In 1915, Mahatma Gandhi became president of the Indian National

11:08.620 --> 11:09.100
Congress,

11:09.800 --> 11:14.840
also known as the Congress Party, founded in 1885 to

11:14.840 --> 11:16.740
fight against British rule in India.

11:17.640 --> 11:22.000
He led the freedom struggle and believed in Ahimsa, the

11:22.000 --> 11:23.460
practice of non-violence,

11:24.020 --> 11:26.060
and used this in the fight for independence.

11:26.060 --> 11:32.240
In 1919, the British government approved a law allowing them

11:32.240 --> 11:33.300
to silence the press

11:33.300 --> 11:38.400
and imprison political activists without a trial. Things got worse

11:38.400 --> 11:39.520
when hundreds of

11:39.520 --> 11:43.160
innocent Indian civilians were massacred at political meetings.

11:44.160 --> 11:47.560
Now the Indians hated the British more than ever and

11:47.560 --> 11:49.740
were even more determined to fight them.

11:50.680 --> 11:55.220
Gandhi's answer was to create the non-cooperation movement in

11:55.220 --> 11:57.960
1920 to continue the struggle for

11:57.960 --> 12:03.140
Indian independence. This movement was one of Gandhi's first organized

12:03.140 --> 12:05.120
acts of civil disobedience.

12:06.240 --> 12:10.640
In this same year, the Indian National Congress reorganized itself

12:10.640 --> 12:12.840
and performed acts of civil

12:12.840 --> 12:17.600
disobedience like the salt march in 1930 to protest against

12:17.600 --> 12:19.160
British taxes on salt.

12:20.420 --> 12:25.800
Gandhi decided to march 388 kilometres from his home to

12:25.800 --> 12:28.240
the Arabian Sea. As he marched,

12:28.780 --> 12:33.160
others joined him. By the 5th of April 1930, they

12:33.160 --> 12:34.080
were several thousand.

12:35.300 --> 12:38.520
Gandhi picked up salt from the ground, the others took

12:38.520 --> 12:41.760
salt too, but the British saw this act as a

12:41.760 --> 12:45.420
crime. The Indians were supposed to buy salt from them,

12:45.880 --> 12:48.620
not take it for free. They sent Gandhi

12:48.620 --> 12:53.760
to prison for this. In 1942, Gandhi started the Quit

12:53.760 --> 12:55.980
India movement, which demanded the

12:55.980 --> 13:00.780
end of British rule over India. Marches, protests and freedom

13:00.780 --> 13:01.820
speeches followed,

13:02.280 --> 13:07.320
with many people arrested or killed. Fighting started between the

13:07.320 --> 13:08.340
Muslims and the Hindus,

13:08.860 --> 13:14.160
leading to the Indian Independence Act in 1947, by which

13:14.160 --> 13:16.520
the UK partitioned British India

13:16.520 --> 13:23.060
into two new independent dominions, India and Pakistan. In the

13:23.060 --> 13:25.140
end, Gandhi achieved his objective.

13:26.060 --> 13:31.560
The British flag was lowered and India was independent. Unfortunately,

13:32.080 --> 13:38.320
India didn't live

13:38.320 --> 13:44.360
from 1947 to 1999, mainly because of territorial conflicts over

13:44.360 --> 13:45.600
the Kashmir region.

13:46.660 --> 13:52.780
Tragically, on 30 January 1948, Mahatma Gandhi, the father of

13:52.780 --> 13:53.540
the Indian nation,

13:53.900 --> 13:57.040
was assassinated in New Delhi by a Hindu fanatic.

13:58.180 --> 14:00.980
Ironic that the man who had dedicated his life to

14:00.980 --> 14:03.640
non-violent protest was himself defeated

14:04.080 --> 14:08.200
by a cruel act of violence. Chapter 3 – The

14:08.200 --> 14:09.240
People of India

14:10.580 --> 14:16.460
Imagine approximately 1.35 billion people living in a country

14:16.460 --> 14:18.860
only three times bigger than the USA.

14:20.000 --> 14:24.740
It's not surprising that India is so overpopulated. It has

14:24.740 --> 14:27.100
the second largest population in the world.

14:28.020 --> 14:31.660
More than 80% of the population is Hindu, so

14:31.660 --> 14:34.480
you'd expect Hinduism to be the official religion.

14:35.380 --> 14:40.080
But in fact, India doesn't have an official religion. Hinduism,

14:40.480 --> 14:43.640
Islam, Buddhism, Sikhism and

14:43.640 --> 14:47.220
Genism are just some of the many religions followed by

14:47.220 --> 14:51.020
the people. India is also the world's largest

14:51.020 --> 14:55.220
democracy, and the slogan, One Man, One Vote, is taken

14:55.220 --> 14:58.400
very seriously. Everybody has the right

14:58.400 --> 15:01.080
to vote, even if they live deep in a forest

15:01.080 --> 15:05.340
like Bharat Das Darshandas, an elderly temple priest.

15:06.280 --> 15:09.240
He is the only voter in the remote Geer Forest

15:09.240 --> 15:13.020
in the state of Gujarat. Two policemen travel

15:13.020 --> 15:18.020
through the lion-infested forest to get his vote. The

15:18.020 --> 15:18.940
Caste System

15:19.800 --> 15:23.260
For more than 3,000 years, India has had a

15:23.260 --> 15:26.980
caste system which most people believe came from Brahma,

15:27.460 --> 15:31.900
the Hindu god of creation. This system divides the population

15:31.900 --> 15:33.800
into four main categories,

15:33.800 --> 15:42.000
according to social importance and profession. Brahmins, Kshatriyas, Vaishas and

15:42.000 --> 15:42.540
Shudras.

15:43.540 --> 15:48.000
The delits, also called untouchables, weren't even part of the

15:48.000 --> 15:50.420
caste system because they were so low.

15:51.520 --> 15:54.900
Each caste is represented by a different part of the

15:54.900 --> 15:56.580
body of the Brahma statue.

15:58.260 --> 16:02.500
Joahalal Nehru, the first Prime Minister of India, came from

16:02.500 --> 16:03.420
the Brahmin caste.

16:04.120 --> 16:06.760
This is the highest caste for priests and teachers.

16:08.940 --> 16:13.800
Satartagatama, the Buddha, was a Kshatriya, the second highest caste.

16:14.800 --> 16:16.160
Kshatriyas were warriors

16:16.160 --> 16:21.340
and rulers of towns and cities. Mahatma Gandhi was born

16:21.340 --> 16:24.160
to a family of Vaishas, the caste which

16:24.160 --> 16:31.100
were mainly farmers, merchants and traders. Chandragupta I, ruler of

16:31.100 --> 16:31.940
the Gupta dynasty,

16:32.600 --> 16:37.280
was a Shudra from the lowest caste. Shudras were labourers

16:37.280 --> 16:39.680
without any social and economic rights.

16:40.700 --> 16:47.440
However, Chandragupta I worked hard and became a Kshatriya. Ramnatt

16:47.440 --> 16:49.540
Koven was born a delit

16:49.540 --> 16:53.360
or untouchable. The people who cleaned the streets and the

16:53.360 --> 16:53.580
toilets.

16:54.560 --> 16:57.100
He came from a poor family and grew up in

16:57.100 --> 16:59.520
a poor hut with six brothers and sisters.

17:00.180 --> 17:03.080
He didn't even have a bicycle, so he walked eight

17:03.080 --> 17:05.120
kilometers to school every day.

17:05.940 --> 17:08.880
But believe it or not, he became president of India

17:08.880 --> 17:10.300
in 2017.

17:12.200 --> 17:19.040
Brahmins, priests and teachers.

17:20.520 --> 17:30.700
Vaishas, farmers, traders and merchants. Shudras, labourers, delits, outside the

17:30.700 --> 17:31.320
caste system,

17:32.040 --> 17:37.640
street sweepers and toilet cleaners. The caste system remained unchanged

17:37.640 --> 17:38.600
for centuries,

17:39.460 --> 17:43.000
trapping people into a classification system from which it was

17:43.000 --> 17:44.440
very difficult to escape.

17:45.400 --> 17:48.280
You were born into a caste and could only marry

17:48.280 --> 17:49.900
a person of the same caste.

17:50.680 --> 17:53.400
It was very difficult to move to a higher or

17:53.400 --> 17:56.540
lower caste. In rural communities,

17:57.120 --> 18:01.040
the upper and lower castes usually lived in segregated colonies

18:01.040 --> 18:02.540
and they didn't drink

18:02.540 --> 18:07.040
from the same springs. Brahmins would not accept food or

18:07.040 --> 18:08.580
drink from Shudras.

18:09.420 --> 18:14.100
Today, the caste system still exists, mainly in rural areas,

18:14.520 --> 18:16.060
but it has much less influence.

18:17.100 --> 18:20.880
In the cities, different castes live side by side and

18:20.880 --> 18:21.880
even into marry.

18:22.960 --> 18:26.700
Some delits and low caste Indians have advanced to occupy

18:26.700 --> 18:28.780
important positions in the country,

18:29.480 --> 18:31.060
like Ramnatt Kavind.

18:32.260 --> 18:33.000
Widows

18:33.780 --> 18:37.540
It might be hard to imagine, but India has another

18:37.540 --> 18:39.300
group of people who are treated

18:39.300 --> 18:43.060
even worse than the untouchables. Widows.

18:43.720 --> 18:48.640
There are approximately 55 million widows in India and their

18:48.640 --> 18:50.220
lives are very difficult.

18:51.200 --> 18:54.280
In the past, when a married man died in India,

18:54.780 --> 18:57.860
his widow used to kill herself on his funeral fire.

18:58.560 --> 19:02.180
Now widows are not expected to do this, but they

19:02.180 --> 19:04.360
are forced to mourn their dead husbands

19:04.360 --> 19:08.160
for the rest of their lives. They are rejected from

19:08.160 --> 19:11.060
society and people think they bring bad luck.

19:11.980 --> 19:15.000
Many widows are thrown out of their homes by their

19:15.000 --> 19:15.860
husbands' families,

19:16.540 --> 19:20.440
who consider them a financial dependent, or by their children

19:20.440 --> 19:21.820
who see them as a burden.

19:22.740 --> 19:26.620
They can't marry again or go to weddings, even of

19:26.620 --> 19:27.300
their own children.

19:27.860 --> 19:32.000
They must wear white because in Hinduism, white is the

19:32.000 --> 19:32.880
colour of mourning.

19:33.780 --> 19:37.480
Even worse, widows are not allowed to work and provide

19:37.480 --> 19:38.040
for themselves,

19:38.960 --> 19:42.060
so they are forced to live in poverty, singing prayers

19:42.060 --> 19:45.120
in temples or begging for food and a roof

19:45.120 --> 19:50.420
over their head. Considered useless without a husband, thousands of

19:50.420 --> 19:52.000
them escaped to Brindavana,

19:52.000 --> 19:55.480
known as the city of widows in the north of

19:55.480 --> 19:59.500
India. This is home to more than 20,000 widows

19:59.500 --> 20:02.980
who depend on charity and are simply waiting to die.

20:04.100 --> 20:06.720
Some organisations are trying to help the

20:06.720 --> 20:10.400
widows of Brindavana and give them some money every month,

20:10.980 --> 20:12.800
but as many can't read or write,

20:13.200 --> 20:15.580
they can't even manage to go to the bank to

20:15.580 --> 20:18.980
take their money out. Clearly, there is a long way

20:18.980 --> 20:19.120
to

20:19.120 --> 20:22.260
go to change the attitude to this vulnerable and neglected

20:22.260 --> 20:24.400
section of Indian society.

20:25.280 --> 20:29.000
Chapter 4. Religion, Customs and Language

20:30.240 --> 20:35.480
Religions There are four main religions in India. Hinduism,

20:35.880 --> 20:46.620
80%, Islam, 14%, Christianity, 2%, and Sikhism, 2%. Buddhism and

20:46.620 --> 20:48.580
Genism are also important

20:48.580 --> 20:51.480
and are followed by one percent of the population.

20:53.580 --> 20:57.300
Hinduism To me, Hinduism is more a way of life

20:57.300 --> 20:58.100
than a religion.

20:59.020 --> 21:02.100
It developed from the religion of the Aryans who arrived

21:02.100 --> 21:05.980
in India around 1500 B.C.

21:06.800 --> 21:11.300
Like all Hindus, I believe in one God named Brahman.

21:11.900 --> 21:14.640
Many people think all Hindus are vegetarian,

21:15.410 --> 21:18.040
but that's not true. We are allowed to eat meat,

21:18.480 --> 21:20.360
although I prefer to be a vegetarian.

21:22.780 --> 21:25.440
Islam I come to you in the name of Allah,

21:25.880 --> 21:29.300
the one and only God of the Muslims, to teach

21:29.300 --> 21:29.840
Islamic

21:29.840 --> 21:34.060
law. In Islam, we don't believe in the caste system.

21:34.660 --> 21:37.340
We have our own social classes. We live

21:37.340 --> 21:40.880
according to the laws of the Quran, which prohibit us

21:40.880 --> 21:41.920
from eating pork.

21:41.920 --> 21:43.860
4. Christianity

21:44.860 --> 21:48.560
I am a Roman Catholic, one of many Christian denominations

21:48.560 --> 21:49.640
in India.

21:50.400 --> 21:53.360
I believe in one God, and that every human being

21:53.360 --> 21:56.940
is his child, and a brother or sister of Jesus

21:56.940 --> 22:02.680
Christ. I want to break down the caste system. Sikhism

22:03.380 --> 22:06.500
I am a follower of the Sikh religion, which was

22:06.500 --> 22:10.180
founded by Guru Nanak in the late 15th century.

22:10.860 --> 22:13.900
We believe in one God, and we believe you don't

22:13.900 --> 22:16.480
have to pray or go to a priest to connect

22:16.480 --> 22:17.040
with him.

22:18.060 --> 22:21.960
In the Sikh religion, everyone is equal. We don't have

22:21.960 --> 22:24.400
social classes and don't follow the caste

22:24.400 --> 22:28.040
system. When it comes to food, we can choose to

22:28.040 --> 22:29.320
eat meat or not.

22:30.880 --> 22:31.440
Genism

22:32.280 --> 22:35.640
If you can't live without your mobile phone, you wouldn't

22:35.640 --> 22:38.400
make a very good gen. We don't believe

22:38.400 --> 22:42.000
in material things or showing violence to any living being.

22:42.860 --> 22:44.140
We have got many gods.

22:44.740 --> 22:47.520
We don't believe in the caste system, and we're vegetarian.

22:48.680 --> 22:50.620
Actually, I don't even eat onions

22:50.620 --> 22:53.820
or potatoes, because when you pull them up from the

22:53.820 --> 22:56.760
earth, it damages tiny organisms in there.

22:58.200 --> 22:58.720
Buddhism

22:59.600 --> 23:04.700
Prince Siddhata Gattama, the Buddha, is my hero. He became

23:04.700 --> 23:06.660
enlightened and founded Buddhism

23:06.660 --> 23:11.080
over two and a half thousand years ago. That is

23:11.080 --> 23:14.320
my mission, to have my eyes opened to see how

23:14.320 --> 23:18.100
the world really works. I go to a special place

23:18.100 --> 23:21.720
called an ashram to do yoga and meditation and

23:21.720 --> 23:26.120
to teach religion. I'm vegetarian, but it's not a rule

23:26.120 --> 23:28.840
among Buddhists. I don't believe in the

23:28.840 --> 23:32.320
caste system, and I don't believe in the existence of

23:32.320 --> 23:33.440
just one God.

23:34.700 --> 23:36.520
Customs and Beliefs

23:37.260 --> 23:40.940
Holy cow is a way of showing surprise in English,

23:41.500 --> 23:44.260
but did you know that cows really are holy to

23:44.260 --> 23:48.720
Hindus? In Hinduism, the mother figure is like a goddess.

23:49.580 --> 23:51.740
Since cows give milk and have a

23:51.740 --> 23:56.020
gentle nature, they are associated with mothers. They are considered

23:56.020 --> 23:58.620
holy, and Hindus idolise them.

23:59.430 --> 24:02.960
In India, there are more than 3,000 institutions which

24:02.960 --> 24:05.220
look after old or sick cows.

24:06.720 --> 24:08.060
Symbolism of the Snake

24:08.960 --> 24:13.120
You might think snakes are scary and dangerous, but not

24:13.120 --> 24:13.700
in India.

24:14.620 --> 24:18.440
There the snake is holy, a symbol of rebirth, death

24:18.440 --> 24:21.320
and mortality, because it sheds its skin

24:21.320 --> 24:26.100
and is reborn. All around India, you can see cobras

24:26.100 --> 24:27.840
made from wood or stone.

24:28.880 --> 24:32.660
Some Indians believe that if you accidentally kill a cobra,

24:33.100 --> 24:35.000
it must be cremated like a human.

24:35.980 --> 24:40.120
In addition, both Hindus and Buddhists believe in the holiness

24:40.120 --> 24:42.360
of a serpent God called naga,

24:43.100 --> 24:45.720
and every year they have a procession in its honour.

24:47.000 --> 24:51.880
Hindus idolise snakes in temples, offering them milk, incense and

24:51.880 --> 24:52.160
prayers.

24:53.820 --> 24:54.500
Language

24:55.380 --> 24:59.840
Hindi and English are the official languages of India, although

24:59.840 --> 25:01.840
Sanskrit is spoken by Hindus,

25:02.460 --> 25:06.520
Buddhists and Jens. At the time of British rule in

25:06.520 --> 25:08.900
India, the country was divided into many

25:08.900 --> 25:13.140
states with their own dialects, and 22 different languages were

25:13.140 --> 25:15.720
spoken. English was a common

25:15.720 --> 25:18.640
language for people of all the different areas to communicate

25:18.640 --> 25:21.400
with each other. It remained the

25:21.400 --> 25:24.460
language of communication after the British left the country.

25:25.700 --> 25:29.340
English is widely spoken in the country today, and ironically,

25:29.860 --> 25:31.940
India is the largest English-speaking

25:31.940 --> 25:37.200
nation in the world. Most colleges and universities use English

25:37.200 --> 25:39.240
for teaching, and it has become a

25:39.240 --> 25:42.700
language of status. If you want to study at university

25:42.700 --> 25:45.860
and get a good job, you must know English.

25:46.660 --> 25:51.400
However, don't assume that all Indians speak English fluently. They

25:51.400 --> 25:53.620
don't. Also, understanding

25:53.620 --> 25:58.540
their accent can sometimes be quite a challenge. The elephant

25:58.540 --> 26:01.000
holds a special place in Indian culture,

26:01.560 --> 26:05.520
particularly in the ancient temples of Kerala, south-western India,

26:06.100 --> 26:07.340
which are home to hundreds

26:07.340 --> 26:12.660
of captive elephants. Hindus believe elephants are holy animals, the

26:12.660 --> 26:14.740
reincarnation of Lord Ganesh,

26:14.740 --> 26:18.000
a god with an elephant head who rides on a

26:18.000 --> 26:18.600
tiny mouse.

26:20.260 --> 26:24.300
Many tourists come to Kerala to admire the elephants, particularly

26:24.300 --> 26:25.880
during festival season,

26:26.460 --> 26:30.240
December to May, when the animals are decorated with ornaments

26:30.240 --> 26:31.980
and exhibited through the streets.

26:32.960 --> 26:37.300
It's an extravagant and colourful spectacle, but many people think

26:37.300 --> 26:44.720
it's cruel, as the elephants

26:44.720 --> 26:47.300
are houts. Lifestyle

26:48.080 --> 26:52.080
Indian culture is full of unique traditions and customs.

26:53.220 --> 26:56.360
One of these practices is the habit of being late.

26:57.560 --> 26:59.700
In India, time has little meaning.

27:00.680 --> 27:03.860
People say the only time Indians aren't late is for

27:03.860 --> 27:06.160
cricket matches, and that's probably because

27:06.160 --> 27:11.280
the umpires aren't Indians. Indians have their own particular way

27:11.280 --> 27:11.680
of dressing.

27:12.580 --> 27:16.460
Women often wear a traditional dress called as sahri, which

27:16.460 --> 27:18.040
is wrapped around the body and

27:18.040 --> 27:22.720
over the shoulder. Men in villages still wear traditional clothes.

27:23.640 --> 27:25.920
A kurda is a shirt that reaches

27:25.920 --> 27:29.420
the knees and is worn over a skirt-like garment.

27:30.520 --> 27:34.480
The salwa kamis, tapered trousers and a long tunic,

27:34.800 --> 27:37.760
is another type of dress that has become very popular

27:37.760 --> 27:39.060
with the younger generation.

27:40.040 --> 27:44.640
Traditional values are very important to Indians. Both in the

27:44.640 --> 27:47.200
past and present, an Indian's family

27:47.200 --> 27:51.120
name is based on his caste, place of origin or

27:51.120 --> 27:54.460
family occupation. Men are still considered

27:54.460 --> 27:57.860
the head of the family, but today women work too

27:57.860 --> 28:01.060
and contribute significantly to the family's

28:01.060 --> 28:05.240
financial situation. Chapter 5. Geography

28:06.460 --> 28:10.960
Great things often happen by accident, and Bharat is one

28:10.960 --> 28:11.280
of them.

28:11.940 --> 28:15.440
Bharat is the official name of the Republic of India,

28:15.940 --> 28:17.940
the seventh biggest country in the world.

28:19.040 --> 28:23.420
Around 50 or 60 million years ago, this enormous peninsula

28:23.420 --> 28:25.280
crashed into Asia,

28:25.840 --> 28:30.840
forming the Himalayas and Hindu Kush mountains. The Himalayas in

28:30.840 --> 28:32.660
the north form the world's

28:32.660 --> 28:37.460
highest mountains. Many of India's rarest animals and plants live

28:37.460 --> 28:39.560
there, and if you're very lucky,

28:40.080 --> 28:44.300
you may even see a snow leopard. The Indian peninsula

28:44.300 --> 28:46.680
is surrounded by the Bay of Bengal

28:46.680 --> 28:51.280
in the southeast, the Arabian Sea in the southwest and

28:51.280 --> 28:52.960
the Indian Ocean in the south.

28:53.800 --> 28:58.320
It's bordered by Bhutan, China and Nepal in the northeast,

28:59.140 --> 29:01.540
Myanmar and Bangladesh in the east,

29:02.000 --> 29:05.780
and Pakistan in the west. One of the things that

29:05.780 --> 29:09.200
make India so unique is its strategic location,

29:10.120 --> 29:15.660
halfway between east and west Asia. From India, Africa is

29:15.660 --> 29:17.920
easily accessible via the Indian Ocean,

29:18.360 --> 29:23.520
and Europe via the Suez Canal. The Strait of Malacca

29:23.520 --> 29:25.620
is one of the most important shipping

29:25.620 --> 29:30.820
routes between the Indian Ocean and the Pacific Ocean. Before

29:30.820 --> 29:33.820
1911, the capital of India was

29:33.820 --> 29:38.580
Kolkata, formerly known as Kolkata, but on the 12th of

29:38.580 --> 29:42.380
December 1911, the British King George VI,

29:42.380 --> 29:46.940
who was also Emperor of India, announced that the capital

29:46.940 --> 29:48.800
should be in Delhi instead,

29:49.520 --> 29:52.600
as this was the political and financial centre of the

29:52.600 --> 29:52.940
country.

29:53.980 --> 30:00.060
The new capital, New Delhi, was inaugurated in 1931. Today,

30:00.540 --> 30:02.520
New Delhi has a population of

30:02.520 --> 30:07.180
almost 19 million people. Climate

30:08.160 --> 30:12.220
There's a variety of terrain in India. In the tar

30:12.220 --> 30:14.680
desert, in the west, the weather is hot

30:14.680 --> 30:18.240
and dry, but if you travel to the northeast, you'll

30:18.240 --> 30:20.940
find jungles. In northern India,

30:21.240 --> 30:25.080
there's an area called the Ganges Plain. It's very fertile

30:25.080 --> 30:27.420
because water from natural springs

30:27.420 --> 30:32.560
runs down the Himalayas, taking fertile sediments with it. This

30:32.560 --> 30:34.440
is very important for growing crops.

30:35.020 --> 30:37.420
Since half the country depends on agriculture.

30:38.900 --> 30:41.760
When there are floods in the Ganges Plain, the farmers

30:41.760 --> 30:43.300
use the water for irrigation.

30:44.800 --> 30:47.940
Floods are common in India because it has so many

30:47.940 --> 30:49.560
rivers and is a peninsula.

30:50.920 --> 30:54.640
There are also the monsoons, which occur from June to

30:54.640 --> 30:55.120
September,

30:55.700 --> 30:58.860
when the direction of the wind changes causing a lot

30:58.860 --> 31:00.340
of heavy rain to fall.

31:01.520 --> 31:02.200
Wildlife

31:03.140 --> 31:06.920
In some parts of India, don't be surprised if you

31:06.920 --> 31:08.560
see an elephant having a massage.

31:09.880 --> 31:14.320
In Guru Vaiya Elephant Sanctuary, there's a spa exclusively for

31:14.320 --> 31:14.580
elephants,

31:15.180 --> 31:20.300
where they get royal treatment, luxurious baths, relaxing massages, and

31:20.300 --> 31:21.180
a special diet.

31:22.260 --> 31:25.540
The elephants here are much more fortunate than those who

31:25.540 --> 31:27.100
work for the tourist industry.

31:28.060 --> 31:31.380
India is home to a wide range of animals thanks

31:31.380 --> 31:32.640
to its varied climate.

31:33.620 --> 31:36.060
It's the only country in the world where you can

31:36.060 --> 31:38.060
find both lions and tigers.

31:39.280 --> 31:42.720
On the coast of the Bay of Bengal lies the

31:42.720 --> 31:46.060
Sunda bands, the world's biggest mangrove forest.

31:46.940 --> 31:49.920
Here you can find tigers swimming in the same rivers

31:49.920 --> 31:52.740
as dolphins, sea turtles, sharks,

31:52.740 --> 31:58.180
and saltwater crocodiles. Sadly, this area is being destroyed by

31:58.180 --> 31:58.560
man,

31:59.060 --> 32:02.320
who hunts animals and cuts down trees for firewood.

32:03.880 --> 32:05.000
The Ganges River

32:06.120 --> 32:09.520
The Ganges got its name from the Hindu goddess Ganges.

32:10.060 --> 32:14.920
This 2,500 kilometer long river plays a very important

32:14.920 --> 32:17.340
role in the lifestyle of the people

32:17.340 --> 32:21.000
who live on its banks. They grow crops along the

32:21.000 --> 32:23.040
river because the earth is very fertile

32:23.600 --> 32:28.220
and they use its water for irrigation. Varanasi, the holiest

32:28.220 --> 32:29.700
city in Hinduism,

32:30.000 --> 32:33.840
is located on the banks of the Ganges. People throw

32:33.840 --> 32:36.140
the ashes of their dead relatives into the

32:36.140 --> 32:39.300
river as they believe it sends the ashes to heaven.

32:40.580 --> 32:43.220
The Ganges is the fifth most contaminated

32:43.220 --> 32:46.760
river in the world, but that doesn't stop it from

32:46.760 --> 32:49.820
being India's most important and holy river

32:49.820 --> 32:54.560
to more than one billion Indians. Locals bathe in the

32:54.560 --> 32:56.120
Ganges, drink from it,

32:56.500 --> 33:01.140
and perform purification rituals in it. At the Kumba Mela

33:01.140 --> 33:01.480
festival,

33:02.240 --> 33:05.720
millions of people come to wash away their sins. The

33:05.720 --> 33:07.680
festival takes place in Alabad,

33:07.680 --> 33:12.320
a city in northern India where three important rivers meet.

33:13.140 --> 33:16.760
Crowds of people stand on the riverbank at Sangam, the

33:16.760 --> 33:18.540
meeting point of these three rivers,

33:19.120 --> 33:22.380
reciting Hindu scriptures as they wait for their turn to

33:22.380 --> 33:23.760
enter the cold water.

33:24.680 --> 33:27.900
Religious leaders from Hindu monasteries lead the ceremony.

33:28.600 --> 33:31.140
They throw flowers at the people in the water shouting,

33:31.720 --> 33:36.760
long live the Ganges, chapter 6, famous places and attractions.

33:38.520 --> 33:39.560
The Taj Mahal

33:40.220 --> 33:43.680
The Taj Mahal in Agra is one of the seven

33:43.680 --> 33:45.120
wonders of the modern world.

33:46.160 --> 33:50.700
You may think $827 million is a lot to spend

33:50.700 --> 33:51.760
on someone you love,

33:52.380 --> 33:57.640
but Emperor Shah Jahan didn't think twice. In the 17th

33:57.640 --> 33:57.640
century,

33:57.640 --> 34:00.720
he built the Taj Mahal as a symbol of love

34:00.720 --> 34:03.500
in memory of his third and favorite wife,

34:04.020 --> 34:09.560
the Persian princess Mumtaz Mahal. Shah loved Mumtaz with all

34:09.560 --> 34:10.180
his heart,

34:10.720 --> 34:13.940
and when she died, while giving birth to their 14th

34:13.940 --> 34:15.820
child, he was heartbroken.

34:16.740 --> 34:19.860
He wanted to do something to honor her, so he

34:19.860 --> 34:22.840
designed and ordered the building of the world's

34:22.840 --> 34:26.580
most beautiful tomb on the banks of the Yamuna River.

34:27.560 --> 34:31.880
It took 20,000 workers almost 22 years to build

34:31.880 --> 34:34.720
this spectacular mausoleum from white marble,

34:35.260 --> 34:40.380
with floral decorations made from precious stones. Every year, around

34:40.380 --> 34:41.760
6 million people

34:41.760 --> 34:44.720
visit the Taj Mahal and admire its splendor.

34:46.100 --> 34:46.860
Mumbai

34:47.760 --> 34:51.400
Mumbai is the most overpopulated city in India.

34:51.940 --> 34:57.140
It's busy, crowded and unpredictable. Don't be surprised to see

34:57.140 --> 34:58.660
a poor hut next to a

34:58.660 --> 35:02.320
multi-million dollar home, or a national park in the

35:02.320 --> 35:04.440
middle of the city with wild animals

35:04.440 --> 35:09.940
walking around freely. Almost 14 million people live in Mumbai.

35:10.420 --> 35:11.940
That's more than twice the number

35:11.940 --> 35:16.500
of inhabitants per square kilometre in New York. What's more,

35:16.960 --> 35:20.500
by 2020, it's estimated that Mumbai

35:20.500 --> 35:23.920
will have a population of 27 million people.

35:25.460 --> 35:29.700
Mumbai and New York have their similarities, but pace isn't

35:29.700 --> 35:30.220
one of them.

35:30.980 --> 35:33.400
If you're in a hurry, don't try to send a

35:33.400 --> 35:35.600
package to a foreign country from the Indian

35:35.600 --> 35:40.200
post office. A special person, called a package waller, puts

35:40.200 --> 35:42.120
your package in a cloth sack

35:42.120 --> 35:45.840
and seals it with a wax stamp, which takes over

35:45.840 --> 35:46.240
an hour.

35:47.040 --> 35:50.560
Riding a train in Mumbai during rush hour is an

35:50.560 --> 35:52.340
experience you'll never forget.

35:53.140 --> 35:57.140
The Indian Railway Company tries to fit 500 people into

35:57.140 --> 35:59.180
a train carriage meant for 188.

36:00.880 --> 36:04.780
The rest sit on the roof. Is that why around

36:04.780 --> 36:08.920
3000 people die in train-related accidents every year?

36:09.840 --> 36:11.020
Film City

36:11.960 --> 36:16.780
Who hasn't heard of Bollywood? The Hindi language film industry.

36:17.680 --> 36:21.400
The name comes from a combination of Bombay, now known

36:21.400 --> 36:24.080
as Mumbai, and Hollywood, the American

36:24.080 --> 36:30.340
equivalent. Unlike Hollywood, Bollywood isn't an actual place, but Film

36:30.340 --> 36:33.150
City is. It's located in

36:33.150 --> 36:37.630
Mumbai and almost all Bollywood films are made there. At

36:37.630 --> 36:39.830
Film City, there are many different types

36:39.830 --> 36:45.470
of film locations, including lakes, gardens, villages, a temple, a

36:45.470 --> 36:47.990
prison, a court and a waterfall.

36:49.170 --> 36:51.950
You can take a guided tour and visit film sets.

36:53.130 --> 36:56.210
Those who prefer to be in a Bollywood film and

36:56.210 --> 36:59.130
not just visit the set of one can spend time

36:59.130 --> 37:02.810
in a popular shopping and dining district, where foreigners are

37:02.810 --> 37:04.610
often asked if they would like to

37:04.610 --> 37:10.510
be extras. Maybe 800 rupees, around 10 euros, isn't much

37:10.510 --> 37:13.170
for a day's work, but the experience is

37:13.170 --> 37:17.250
certainly worth a lot more. Varanasi

37:18.030 --> 37:20.830
For some tourists, it's quite a shock to see the

37:20.830 --> 37:23.790
sight of unburned body parts floating on the

37:23.790 --> 37:28.310
tangies. That's a sure sign that they're in Varanasi, the

37:28.310 --> 37:31.050
city of 23,000 temples.

37:32.010 --> 37:35.750
Almost two and a half million people visit Varanasi every

37:35.750 --> 37:38.190
year. Many of them are close to

37:38.190 --> 37:40.690
the end of their life and they come to bathe

37:40.690 --> 37:44.390
in the Holy River. In Hinduism and Buddhism,

37:45.050 --> 37:49.470
Nirvana is the highest state that someone can reach. It's

37:49.470 --> 37:50.330
a state of enlightenment,

37:50.330 --> 37:55.810
a place of perfect peace and happiness. Hindus believe that

37:55.810 --> 37:58.050
dying in Varanasi brings salvation

37:58.640 --> 38:02.310
and Nirvana, so they travel to the city as soon

38:02.310 --> 38:04.130
as they realize they are close to death.

38:05.110 --> 38:08.710
After death, they are purified in the Ganges and then

38:08.710 --> 38:12.370
cremated. Any unburned body parts are thrown

38:12.370 --> 38:17.090
into the river. Gats are places with steps that lead

38:17.090 --> 38:18.690
down to the banks of the river.

38:19.390 --> 38:23.630
In Varanasi, some Gats are for bathing or religious ceremonies,

38:24.410 --> 38:28.370
while others are only used for cremations. CHAPTER 7

38:29.370 --> 38:30.130
Festivals

38:30.910 --> 38:35.010
Indians celebrate a multitude of festivals that contribute to the

38:35.010 --> 38:36.250
country's rich culture,

38:36.650 --> 38:41.690
traditions and spirituality. Some of the festivals are celebrated all

38:41.690 --> 38:42.470
around the country,

38:42.470 --> 38:47.910
while others are only celebrated in specific regions. Being a

38:47.910 --> 38:49.370
part of any of these festivals

38:49.370 --> 38:53.390
is a colourful experience. DIVALI

38:54.330 --> 38:58.130
Horrendous traffic jams and a spectacular fireworks display

38:58.130 --> 39:02.430
announced that Diwali, the Hindu festival of lights, has arrived.

39:03.590 --> 39:04.770
This is India's biggest

39:04.770 --> 39:10.130
and most important holiday. The name Diwali means rose of

39:10.130 --> 39:12.450
lighted lamps, and it's easy to

39:12.450 --> 39:16.770
see why. The whole country is illuminated by lamps called

39:16.770 --> 39:19.270
Dias, candles and fireworks,

39:20.010 --> 39:23.950
as Hindus celebrate the triumph of light over dark and

39:23.950 --> 39:25.430
of good over evil.

39:26.690 --> 39:31.070
Hindus believe in one true God, Brahman, but they have

39:31.070 --> 39:33.730
many other gods too. One of the most

39:33.730 --> 39:39.170
important gods is Lord Rama, who had many adventures. In

39:39.170 --> 39:41.750
one of these, he killed the Demon King

39:41.750 --> 39:47.250
Ravana, who had captured Rama's beloved wife Sita. The lamps

39:47.250 --> 39:47.850
that illuminate

39:47.850 --> 39:52.530
India during Diwali are to help Rama and Sita find

39:52.530 --> 39:55.330
their way home after the defeat of the demon.

39:56.610 --> 40:02.290
In Tharavi, a very poor area in Mumbai, 2,500

40:02.290 --> 40:05.770
potter families spend days making Dias before

40:05.770 --> 40:10.350
the festival starts. Men make them from clay and bake

40:10.350 --> 40:12.430
them in ovens. After that,

40:12.650 --> 40:15.710
women paint them and children help to pack them for

40:15.710 --> 40:19.010
sale. Everybody plays a part in the festivities.

40:20.590 --> 40:24.890
Like Christmas, Diwali is a holiday where families come together

40:24.890 --> 40:26.730
to share sweets and gifts.

40:27.690 --> 40:31.450
It's celebrated for five days, and on each day, different

40:31.450 --> 40:33.430
prayers are recited and different

40:33.430 --> 40:39.670
rituals are performed. In certain regions of Rajasthan, women participate

40:39.670 --> 40:41.090
in a special ritual,

40:41.910 --> 40:44.890
dancing in a circle with a flaming pot on their

40:44.890 --> 40:49.670
heads. In Goa, people build big, scary statues

40:49.670 --> 40:55.090
of the legendary tyrant Narakasura, a cruel and unpopular leader

40:55.090 --> 40:57.010
who try to kill one of

40:57.010 --> 41:02.990
beloved gods, Lord Krishna. Lord Krishna cut off Narakasura's head,

41:03.610 --> 41:07.090
and in celebration of this, the huge statues are burnt

41:07.090 --> 41:09.070
on the night before Diwali.

41:10.190 --> 41:11.550
Durga Puja

41:12.490 --> 41:16.610
Durga Puja is both an arts festival and a religious

41:16.610 --> 41:26.990
celebration. It is celebrated mainly in West

41:26.990 --> 41:30.730
is in honor of the goddess Durga, the symbol of

41:30.730 --> 41:33.590
divine feminine energy and her victory

41:33.590 --> 41:40.610
over the evil buffalo demon Mahishasura. Kolkata's artisans spend a

41:40.610 --> 41:42.150
year preparing for the festival.

41:43.030 --> 41:47.210
They make special platforms and display ten armed statues of

41:47.210 --> 41:48.890
the goddess Durga on them.

41:49.630 --> 41:53.670
During the festival, people go from platform to platform to

41:53.670 --> 41:55.090
see these works of art,

41:55.090 --> 41:58.290
and on the last day, they join a procession to

41:58.290 --> 42:01.350
the Ganges River, where the statues are submerged

42:01.350 --> 42:06.390
in the water. Durga Puja has a number of religious

42:06.390 --> 42:10.130
rituals. In one of them, a small banana plant

42:10.130 --> 42:13.830
is dressed in a sari, bazed in a nearby river

42:13.830 --> 42:17.830
and then used to attract Durga's energy and holy

42:17.830 --> 42:20.350
presence. Huli

42:21.350 --> 42:25.270
Huli, known as the festival of colors, celebrates the arrival

42:25.270 --> 42:27.810
of spring and the victory of good

42:27.810 --> 42:32.890
over evil. In most places, Huli is celebrated for two

42:32.890 --> 42:35.110
days, and if you don't mind getting wet

42:35.110 --> 42:38.850
and dirty, it can be a lot of fun. The

42:38.850 --> 42:42.750
first night, Holikadhan starts with a public fire

42:42.750 --> 42:48.170
symbolizing the burning of Holikad, the devil. People have parties

42:48.170 --> 42:50.330
and dance under water sprinklers.

42:51.470 --> 42:55.950
Rangwali Huli starts the next morning. People put color all

42:55.950 --> 42:57.850
over each other's faces and throw

42:57.850 --> 43:02.510
water on each other while saying, don't be offended, it's

43:02.510 --> 43:06.570
Huli. Some of them first put coconut oil on

43:06.570 --> 43:09.570
their skin, which makes it easier to clean, so they

43:09.570 --> 43:11.950
won't look like a walking rainbow for a week

43:11.950 --> 43:17.330
after the festival. The British band Coldplay filmed the video

43:17.330 --> 43:18.270
clip of their song,

43:18.690 --> 43:22.630
Him for the Weekend at the Huli Festival, chapter 8.

43:23.650 --> 43:25.350
Food Glorious Food

43:26.650 --> 43:31.230
India's multinational population and a significant role in the spice

43:31.230 --> 43:31.670
trade

43:31.670 --> 43:37.130
explain why Indian food explodes with flavor. A variety of

43:37.130 --> 43:39.190
factors have influenced Indian cooking,

43:39.670 --> 43:42.830
like the chili pepper brought from Mexico by the Portuguese,

43:43.870 --> 43:45.750
the chutney developed by British

43:45.750 --> 43:50.310
housewives and their Indian cooks, and new food ideas introduced

43:50.310 --> 43:52.370
by Indians returning from their

43:52.370 --> 43:56.690
travels. Many of the dishes are based on rice, grains

43:56.690 --> 44:00.510
and pulses. Although the food differs from

44:00.510 --> 44:03.430
region to region, you can be certain that everything is

44:03.430 --> 44:05.170
made with plenty of spices,

44:05.650 --> 44:11.910
like garam masala, a combination of dried spices. Chutney is

44:11.910 --> 44:14.270
an important ingredient in Indian dishes.

44:15.250 --> 44:18.790
Many of us have eaten sweet mango chutney, sour mint

44:18.790 --> 44:21.230
chutney or hot chili chutney,

44:21.890 --> 44:27.310
but you've probably never tried chapra, red ant chutney. A

44:27.310 --> 44:30.050
tribe from Bastar in Chhattisgarh

44:30.050 --> 44:34.030
collects tons of stinging biting ants and their eggs, which

44:34.030 --> 44:36.890
are crushed, dried and ground into a

44:36.890 --> 44:44.230
powder. Tomatoes, cilantro, garlic, ginger, chili, salt and sugar are

44:44.230 --> 44:45.750
added to make the hot,

44:45.890 --> 44:50.490
spicy orange-coloured chutney. If you don't mind eating ants,

44:51.370 --> 44:53.590
chapra is very healthy because

44:53.590 --> 44:59.030
ants contain an acid with medicinal properties. Exotic Foods

44:59.960 --> 45:03.890
If you think Indian food is only about spices, curries

45:03.890 --> 45:07.390
and vegetables, think again. In Assam,

45:07.850 --> 45:12.830
people eat a delicacy called eripolu. It's made from the

45:12.830 --> 45:16.090
pupa of silkworms and served with

45:16.090 --> 45:22.250
chorissa, a dish made from fermented bamboo shoots. Another exotic

45:22.250 --> 45:22.790
dish,

45:23.190 --> 45:26.590
sore potter, is a kind of stew that's eaten in

45:26.590 --> 45:28.950
Goa. It looks quite harmless,

45:29.530 --> 45:34.250
but it's made from a pig's internal organs. Dishes made

45:34.250 --> 45:36.410
from dried fish are another delicacy

45:36.410 --> 45:40.670
in many parts of India. Nakam takes the prize for

45:40.670 --> 45:42.830
being the smellyest of all the fish dishes.

45:43.440 --> 45:47.350
It's a curry made from dried fish mixed with vegetables

45:47.350 --> 45:49.070
and distilled ashes.

45:50.170 --> 45:56.750
The Tali Indian restaurants offer a multitude of dishes,

45:57.370 --> 46:00.970
so the Tali, the Hindi word for a large plate,

46:01.490 --> 46:04.410
is the perfect solution for indecisive people,

46:05.010 --> 46:08.910
and it's popular in many regions of the country. It

46:08.910 --> 46:10.950
consists of a selection of curries,

46:10.950 --> 46:16.070
vegetables, sauces and yogurt. The food is served in small

46:16.070 --> 46:18.010
bowls on a round tray

46:18.010 --> 46:21.290
with a mountain of rice in the middle. It comes

46:21.290 --> 46:24.030
with chutney, pickles and poppodums,

46:24.510 --> 46:28.710
a thin round crispy bread. The dishes in the Tali

46:28.710 --> 46:30.590
are eaten in a special order.

46:31.350 --> 46:34.950
For example, you start with the vegetables, followed by rice

46:34.950 --> 46:37.530
mixed with a spicy lentil sauce

46:37.530 --> 46:42.570
called sambha. Next, the spiciest of the sauces is served,

46:43.190 --> 46:44.630
and then the rasam,

46:44.890 --> 46:48.870
a sauce made from tomatoes. You eat a small portion

46:48.870 --> 46:50.450
of rice with each of the sauces.

46:51.410 --> 46:54.850
By this time, your palate will be on fire, so

46:54.850 --> 46:57.070
you'll be ready for the yogurt mixed with rice.

46:58.030 --> 47:03.230
For dessert, the Tali sometimes includes something sweet. Tali is

47:03.230 --> 47:04.270
good for your digestion,

47:04.820 --> 47:09.890
because it's a balanced meal. Eating habits. It's not just

47:09.890 --> 47:11.570
the food in India that's unusual,

47:12.390 --> 47:15.890
but also the way it's eaten and served. In Europe,

47:16.270 --> 47:18.390
eating with your hands is not considered

47:18.390 --> 47:23.130
very polite, but in India it's a tradition. In fact,

47:23.290 --> 47:24.470
when you eat with your hands,

47:24.890 --> 47:28.370
you enjoy your food more, because it stimulates the senses.

47:29.030 --> 47:32.710
Indians believe that touching your food helps you feel the

47:32.710 --> 47:34.510
taste, texture and aroma,

47:35.350 --> 47:38.370
but you must only use your right hand because the

47:38.370 --> 47:40.810
left hand is considered unclean.

47:41.730 --> 47:44.690
In the south of India, it's a tradition to serve

47:44.690 --> 47:47.190
food on banana leaves instead of plates.

47:48.090 --> 47:51.390
Firstly, it's healthier because when you put hot food on

47:51.390 --> 47:52.210
a banana leaf,

47:52.210 --> 47:54.950
it releases nutrients that are good for you.

47:55.670 --> 48:01.590
Secondly, it tastes and smells better. Thirdly, it's environmentally friendly,

48:02.150 --> 48:04.350
but the best part is that there are no plates

48:04.350 --> 48:05.830
to wash at the end of the meal.

48:06.630 --> 48:11.170
Maybe we should all try this idea. Chapter 9. Famous

48:11.170 --> 48:11.610
People

48:12.970 --> 48:17.150
Mahatma Gandhi Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi

48:17.710 --> 48:21.550
was known to his people as Mahatma, which means Great

48:21.550 --> 48:24.970
Soul, or Bapu, which means Father.

48:26.370 --> 48:32.270
Gandhi was born in Pobanda, India, in 1869. He came

48:32.270 --> 48:33.730
from a well-respected family,

48:34.310 --> 48:38.430
and his parents arranged for him to marry Kasturba Mahanji

48:38.430 --> 48:39.510
when he was thirteen.

48:40.690 --> 48:43.810
This may seem strange to you, but for an Indian

48:43.810 --> 48:45.250
boy it was expected.

48:45.990 --> 48:49.450
His parents wanted him to become a lawyer, so he

48:49.450 --> 48:52.270
studied law in London and then went to South

48:52.270 --> 48:56.590
Africa to find employment. While he was travelling on a

48:56.590 --> 48:59.410
train one day, Gandhi was asked to leave

48:59.410 --> 49:02.310
the first-class carriage even though he had a valid

49:02.310 --> 49:06.070
ticket. The reason? His skin colour.

49:06.990 --> 49:09.810
He was furious, and this marked the start of his

49:09.810 --> 49:11.850
fight against racial discrimination.

49:12.530 --> 49:19.410
In 1894, Gandhi founded the Natal Indian Congress, and protested

49:19.410 --> 49:22.570
against injustice to Indians in South Africa.

49:23.870 --> 49:27.530
Gandhi stayed in South Africa for twenty years, and then

49:27.530 --> 49:30.090
returned to India, but things weren't

49:30.090 --> 49:34.770
better there. The British discriminated against the Indians, and Gandhi

49:34.770 --> 49:36.850
refused to accept this,

49:36.850 --> 49:40.450
so he dedicated his life to fighting for equality.

49:41.670 --> 49:46.910
He organised non-violent civil disobedience campaigns in which people

49:46.910 --> 49:48.770
didn't go to work or eat,

49:49.270 --> 49:53.230
sat in the streets, or boy-cotted the courts. These

49:53.230 --> 49:55.710
acts may seem small, but when thousands

49:55.710 --> 49:58.430
of people did them at the same time, it had

49:58.430 --> 50:03.250
a huge impact. Gandhi was arrested many times and

50:03.250 --> 50:07.850
imprisoned, but his many followers and worldwide support made sure

50:07.850 --> 50:09.350
that he didn't stay in prison

50:09.350 --> 50:13.270
for long, especially because the British were afraid of what

50:13.270 --> 50:15.470
might happen if he died in prison.

50:16.870 --> 50:20.490
Finally, Gandhi's efforts paid off, and he won the battle

50:20.490 --> 50:22.670
for independence for the Indian people.

50:23.650 --> 50:28.010
Sadly, Gandhi the pacifist was shot and killed by a

50:28.010 --> 50:30.630
Hindu fanatic on his way to prayers in New

50:30.630 --> 50:34.270
Delhi on the 30th of January, 1948.

50:36.170 --> 50:36.770
Mother Teresa

50:38.400 --> 50:43.850
Mother Teresa won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1979. In

50:43.850 --> 50:46.950
1985, she received the Medal of Freedom,

50:47.650 --> 50:50.510
the highest honour awarded by the President of the United

50:50.510 --> 50:51.770
States to a civilian.

50:52.730 --> 50:56.110
She devoted her life to charity work and was declared

50:56.110 --> 50:58.070
a saint in 2016.

51:00.030 --> 51:05.850
Mother Teresa was born in Scopia, Macedonia, in 1910. At

51:05.850 --> 51:08.550
the age of 18, she joined a group of nuns

51:08.550 --> 51:08.870
in

51:08.870 --> 51:13.770
Ireland, where she learned English. After training, she was sent

51:13.770 --> 51:16.290
to India, where she became a nun in

51:16.290 --> 51:21.310
1931. In that year, she started teaching in a school

51:21.310 --> 51:25.650
for girls in Kolkata. At 36, she discovered

51:25.650 --> 51:29.010
her mission in life, to help the sick and the

51:29.010 --> 51:32.610
poor. She learned how to give medical care and

51:32.610 --> 51:36.590
started doing charity work. It wasn't easy, and there were

51:36.590 --> 51:39.390
times when she herself had to beg for food.

51:40.590 --> 51:46.110
In 1950, Mother Teresa founded The Missionaries of Charity, an

51:46.110 --> 51:48.250
organisation that cared for the poor,

51:48.730 --> 51:53.570
hungry, homeless, disabled, and anyone who was not accepted in

51:53.570 --> 51:53.910
society.

51:54.550 --> 51:58.650
She opened many charity houses around the world, but is

51:58.650 --> 52:00.610
best known for her work in India.

52:02.190 --> 52:05.870
Mother Teresa died at the age of 87, on the

52:05.870 --> 52:10.510
5th of September 1997. At the time of her death,

52:10.910 --> 52:16.190
the Missionaries of Charity were running 610 missions in 123

52:16.190 --> 52:17.190
countries.

52:19.590 --> 52:20.310
Sashintendulka

52:21.470 --> 52:26.390
People say that if cricket were a religion, Sashintendulka would

52:26.390 --> 52:27.070
be the god.

52:28.050 --> 52:31.650
The retired cricketer and captain is the greatest and most

52:31.650 --> 52:34.390
admired Indian cricketer of all time.

52:35.310 --> 52:38.450
No other player has ever scored so many runs in

52:38.450 --> 52:39.390
international cricket.

52:40.270 --> 52:44.370
Tendulka received numerous awards for his notable achievements in sport,

52:44.370 --> 52:49.450
and after his final match in 2013, he was awarded

52:49.450 --> 52:52.890
the Bharat Ratna, the highest award given by

52:52.890 --> 52:57.290
the Indian government to a civilian. No other sport person

52:57.290 --> 52:59.310
has ever received this award.

53:00.670 --> 53:05.730
Tendulka was born in Mumbai in 1973. He started playing

53:05.730 --> 53:06.910
cricket when he was 11

53:06.910 --> 53:11.370
and practised for hours, showing his incredible batting skills while

53:11.370 --> 53:12.250
still at school.

53:13.050 --> 53:17.790
When he was 14, a famous Indian batsman called Sunil

53:17.790 --> 53:19.670
Gavaskar inspired him.

53:20.570 --> 53:24.650
Gavaskar made his international debut when he was 16 and

53:24.650 --> 53:25.870
20 years later,

53:26.230 --> 53:28.590
Tendulka broke Gavaskar's record.

53:29.490 --> 53:34.470
Tendulka was highly motivated and became a champion cricketer, representing

53:34.470 --> 53:35.530
Mumbai and

53:35.530 --> 53:41.630
India in cricket for almost 24 years. In 2011, he

53:41.630 --> 53:43.790
won the cricket world cup with his team,

53:44.210 --> 53:49.950
making India very proud. Chapter 10. Sport. Cricket

53:50.850 --> 53:54.370
There is no doubt that cricket is India's most popular

53:54.370 --> 53:55.990
sport, thanks to the British.

53:56.750 --> 53:59.590
In a cricket match, there are two teams with 11

53:59.590 --> 54:02.770
players in each team. They take turns batting

54:02.770 --> 54:07.070
and fielding. The objective of the batting team is to

54:07.070 --> 54:08.750
score as many runs as possible.

54:09.750 --> 54:12.990
The fielding players run around the cricket field to catch

54:12.990 --> 54:15.030
the ball and stop the batsman

54:15.030 --> 54:18.510
from scoring runs. The winner is the team with the

54:18.510 --> 54:19.770
most runs in an innings,

54:20.550 --> 54:23.130
which is when every player in the team has batted.

54:24.450 --> 54:29.150
Cricket became popular in India in the 17th century. During

54:29.150 --> 54:29.970
the British rule,

54:29.970 --> 54:36.590
the Maharaja, King of Patyala, played and supported cricket. He

54:36.590 --> 54:37.690
was captain of the Indian

54:37.690 --> 54:41.530
cricket team in 1911 and played in first class cricket

54:41.530 --> 54:44.770
matches between 1915 and 1937.

54:46.610 --> 54:51.330
The Maharaja's summer residence, the Child Palace, had the world's

54:51.330 --> 54:52.370
highest cricket ground,

54:52.810 --> 54:57.930
which was 2,250 metres high with forests all around.

54:59.210 --> 55:03.410
India's national team won the Cricket World Cup in 1983

55:03.410 --> 55:07.730
and 2011, as well as other important trophies.

55:08.870 --> 55:12.470
India also holds the world record for winning all the

55:12.470 --> 55:15.270
ICC International Cricket Council

55:15.270 --> 55:20.910
tournaments when MS Thuni was the captain. Field Hockey

55:22.060 --> 55:26.390
Most Indian sports fans consider field hockey the national sport

55:26.390 --> 55:26.930
of India

55:26.930 --> 55:30.290
due to their excellent performances in past Olympics.

55:31.530 --> 55:34.830
In field hockey, there are 11 players in each team.

55:35.650 --> 55:38.170
The objective of the game is to score more

55:38.170 --> 55:41.610
goals than the opposing team by hitting the ball past

55:41.610 --> 55:44.070
the goalkeeper and across the goal line.

55:44.910 --> 55:48.770
Players aren't allowed to kick, hold or carry the ball.

55:49.490 --> 55:51.470
They use wooden hockey sticks instead.

55:51.470 --> 55:57.270
In the beginning, the Indian team was invincible, taking home

55:57.270 --> 55:59.790
six Olympic gold medals from 1928

55:59.790 --> 56:07.610
to 1956 and two more in 1964 and 1980. In

56:07.610 --> 56:11.850
addition, India has won one silver and two bronze Olympic

56:11.850 --> 56:15.650
medals. More hockey medals than any other team in the

56:15.650 --> 56:20.290
world. They also won the 1975 World Cup

56:20.290 --> 56:26.590
tournament in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. But after 1980, they lost

56:26.590 --> 56:27.410
their supremacy,

56:28.150 --> 56:31.350
mainly because of a change in the rules. Until the

56:31.350 --> 56:34.410
early 1970s, hockey was played on grass.

56:35.370 --> 56:40.370
Then, in the mid 1970s, the International Hockey Federation decided

56:40.370 --> 56:41.310
to make it a

56:41.310 --> 56:45.470
obligatory for all international hockey tournaments to be played on

56:45.470 --> 56:46.370
Astroturf.

56:46.930 --> 56:52.250
This change was implemented in the 1976 Montreal Olympics. And

56:52.250 --> 56:53.130
guess what happened?

56:53.910 --> 56:58.310
India didn't even win a bronze medal. There aren't many

56:58.310 --> 57:00.070
Astroturf grounds in India

57:00.070 --> 57:03.450
because they are expensive to lay and difficult to play

57:03.450 --> 57:06.350
on. However, in western countries like

57:06.350 --> 57:10.870
Holland, Germany and Australia, there are lots of Astroturf grounds,

57:11.610 --> 57:15.330
so Europe and Australia have now become the leaders in

57:15.330 --> 57:15.990
field hockey.

57:17.170 --> 57:20.770
Today, field hockey is much more popular than it used

57:20.770 --> 57:23.530
to be, both in India and other countries.

57:24.570 --> 57:28.170
Women also play field hockey and they are very good

57:28.170 --> 57:30.890
at it. According to the International Hockey

57:30.890 --> 57:36.010
Federation, the Indian Women's Hockey Team is ranked 13th and

57:36.010 --> 57:37.570
it is won three gold medals

57:37.570 --> 57:45.370
consecutively in international competitions. Kabadi. Kabadi is a very exciting

57:45.370 --> 57:46.550
team sport that

57:46.550 --> 57:50.370
is popular in Indian villages. It dates back to ancient

57:50.370 --> 57:52.550
times and was played by princes

57:52.550 --> 57:56.870
to prove how strong they were. Kabadi is played on

57:56.870 --> 57:59.350
a small field divided into two halves.

57:59.920 --> 58:03.390
There are two teams of seven players and each team

58:03.390 --> 58:05.570
takes turns sending a raider

58:05.570 --> 58:10.050
and attacking player into the other half. The raider has

58:10.050 --> 58:11.370
to eliminate his opponents

58:11.800 --> 58:14.590
and then return to his half of the field without

58:14.590 --> 58:16.490
being stopped by the defenders.

58:17.490 --> 58:20.350
At the same time, he has to hold his breath

58:20.350 --> 58:24.270
and chant Kabadi Kabadi Kabadi the whole time.

58:24.850 --> 58:30.110
The team that eliminates more opponents wins. The founder of

58:30.110 --> 58:32.850
Buddhism, Prince Siddhata Gattama,

58:33.310 --> 58:37.490
played Kabadi with his friends. The game requires both intelligence

58:37.490 --> 58:39.110
and physical strength.

58:39.910 --> 58:42.610
You also have to be in good shape and be

58:42.610 --> 58:45.710
able to anticipate what the opponent is going to do.

58:46.470 --> 58:49.990
India has been very successful at this sport, winning all

58:49.990 --> 58:51.570
the Kabadi World Cup tournaments

58:51.570 --> 58:56.170
and gold medals in all the Asian games. Chapter 11.

58:57.150 --> 58:59.870
Films. More Fact than Fiction.

59:01.730 --> 59:05.730
In the past, Indian films were mainly the Bollywood romantic

59:05.730 --> 59:08.030
musicals of the Hindi language film

59:08.030 --> 59:13.210
industry. But more recently, English films about India expose the

59:13.210 --> 59:14.630
Western world to some of the

59:14.630 --> 59:21.150
country's more serious problems, like poor sanitation, poverty, pollution, child

59:21.150 --> 59:21.510
marriage

59:21.510 --> 59:25.890
and the terrible treatment of widows. Many of these films

59:25.890 --> 59:27.510
are based on true stories

59:27.510 --> 59:31.970
and paint a realistic picture of daily life, projecting images

59:31.970 --> 59:34.110
that remain in the audience's mind

59:34.510 --> 59:39.010
even after they leave the cinema. These films show facts

59:39.010 --> 59:40.510
that cannot be ignored.

59:41.810 --> 59:43.590
Toilet. A Love Story.

59:45.070 --> 59:51.010
The Inspiration for Toilet, a Love Story, 2017, came from

59:51.010 --> 59:52.970
the true story of Anita Nari,

59:53.530 --> 59:56.630
a poor Indian woman who discovered after she got married

59:56.630 --> 59:59.090
that her new house didn't have a toilet.

59:59.910 --> 01:00:03.390
This may seem trivial to you, but to Indian women

01:00:03.390 --> 01:00:06.110
who are in danger of being sexually assaulted

01:00:06.110 --> 01:00:11.610
if they relieve themselves outside, it's a serious problem. For

01:00:11.610 --> 01:00:12.250
this reason,

01:00:12.510 --> 01:00:15.070
many women go out in groups when they need to

01:00:15.070 --> 01:00:17.970
go to the toilet and wait until it gets dark

01:00:17.970 --> 01:00:22.050
so that nobody will see them. In the film, Anita

01:00:22.050 --> 01:00:24.190
almost divorces her husband,

01:00:24.790 --> 01:00:27.150
but in the end he builds her a toilet in

01:00:27.150 --> 01:00:29.270
their home and their marriage is saved.

01:00:30.410 --> 01:00:34.570
People relieving themselves in public places is a terrible problem

01:00:34.570 --> 01:00:35.210
in India

01:00:35.210 --> 01:00:39.470
and according to UNICEF, more than half a million people

01:00:39.470 --> 01:00:40.390
still do that.

01:00:41.090 --> 01:00:44.330
The government has initiated a campaign to try and solve

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:44.970
this problem.

01:00:45.930 --> 01:00:49.430
A new mobile phone app tells people where to find

01:00:49.430 --> 01:00:50.350
the nearest toilet,

01:00:50.890 --> 01:00:54.170
and thousands of toilets have been installed around the country,

01:00:54.610 --> 01:00:58.450
but unfortunately, many of them don't actually work.

01:00:59.730 --> 01:01:00.570
Water

01:01:01.730 --> 01:01:08.190
Deeper Metas Water, 2005, examines the social restrictions imposed on

01:01:08.190 --> 01:01:08.710
widows

01:01:08.710 --> 01:01:12.710
and exposes an ancient Hindu law that a widow must

01:01:12.710 --> 01:01:14.910
either marry her dead husband's brother

01:01:15.270 --> 01:01:20.150
or kill herself on her husband's funeral fire. This film

01:01:20.150 --> 01:01:22.470
caused a lot of controversy in India.

01:01:23.130 --> 01:01:26.510
On more than one occasion, the film sets were destroyed

01:01:26.510 --> 01:01:28.530
and Deeper's life was threatened,

01:01:29.250 --> 01:01:33.070
so the Indo-Canadian director moved to the filming from

01:01:33.070 --> 01:01:34.510
India to Sri Lanka.

01:01:35.610 --> 01:01:39.670
Water is set in 1938 at a time when child

01:01:39.670 --> 01:01:41.430
marriage was common in India,

01:01:42.030 --> 01:01:45.150
and even young child widows were discriminated against.

01:01:45.830 --> 01:01:49.970
It centers on the lives of Chuya, a little Indian

01:01:49.970 --> 01:01:52.490
girl who is widowed at the age of eight.

01:01:53.390 --> 01:01:57.030
After the death of her forty-year-old husband, Chuya

01:01:57.030 --> 01:01:59.970
is sent to an ashram where her hair is

01:01:59.970 --> 01:02:03.490
cut off and she has to wear white. She believes

01:02:03.490 --> 01:02:05.750
that her mother will come and take her home,

01:02:06.290 --> 01:02:09.030
but in reality, she is destined to remain in the

01:02:09.030 --> 01:02:11.990
ashram forever because she is now a widow.

01:02:13.230 --> 01:02:14.030
Lion

01:02:14.030 --> 01:02:20.330
The award-winning film Lion, 2016, is based on the

01:02:20.330 --> 01:02:22.770
true story of Saru Brieli,

01:02:23.270 --> 01:02:27.930
a lost little boy who travels 1,600 kilometres alone

01:02:27.930 --> 01:02:31.810
by train to Kolkata trying to find his big brother.

01:02:32.630 --> 01:02:36.530
Saru is put in an orphanage and finally adopted by

01:02:36.530 --> 01:02:39.150
an Australian couple who live in Tasmania.

01:02:40.190 --> 01:02:44.310
Every year, more than 80,000 children go missing in

01:02:44.310 --> 01:02:47.750
India, and over 11 million children spend

01:02:47.750 --> 01:02:51.550
their lives on the streets. Saru is one of them,

01:02:51.970 --> 01:02:54.590
and we see his struggle to survive as a street

01:02:54.590 --> 01:02:58.870
child, sleeping in train stations on a cardboard box and

01:02:58.870 --> 01:03:02.810
eating food from rubbish bins. As an adult,

01:03:03.250 --> 01:03:06.090
he lives a good life with his adopted family, but

01:03:06.090 --> 01:03:08.490
is tormented by memories of his childhood.

01:03:09.650 --> 01:03:13.710
After 25 years, Saru decides to try and find his

01:03:13.710 --> 01:03:14.890
biological mother.

01:03:15.670 --> 01:03:19.050
With the help of Google satellite maps and faint memories

01:03:19.050 --> 01:03:20.670
of the night he lost his brother,

01:03:21.330 --> 01:03:23.930
he struggles to try and locate the village where he

01:03:23.930 --> 01:03:26.630
was born and the family he left behind.

01:03:28.470 --> 01:03:29.670
Slumdog Millionaire

01:03:31.070 --> 01:03:35.450
Slumdog Millionaire, 2008, is based on the life of a

01:03:35.450 --> 01:03:38.330
real person named Sushil Kumar.

01:03:39.150 --> 01:03:42.590
The word Slumdog refers to someone who lives in a

01:03:42.590 --> 01:03:45.370
slum, a very poor area of the town.

01:03:46.410 --> 01:03:50.790
Sushil, 26, came from a very poor family that didn't

01:03:50.790 --> 01:03:52.910
even have money to buy a TV set,

01:03:53.650 --> 01:03:57.290
but his life changed forever when he won $1 million

01:03:57.290 --> 01:04:00.410
on the Indian version of the TV show

01:04:00.410 --> 01:04:04.510
who wants to be a millionaire. To a series of

01:04:04.510 --> 01:04:04.850
flashbacks,

01:04:05.490 --> 01:04:09.550
Slumdog Millionaire shows the events that led Sushil to win

01:04:09.550 --> 01:04:10.150
the competition.

01:04:11.370 --> 01:04:15.510
We see the terrible living conditions and poor sanitation in

01:04:15.510 --> 01:04:18.130
Dharavi, a famous slum in contemporary

01:04:18.130 --> 01:04:22.490
Mumbai. For six children, two of whom came from the

01:04:22.490 --> 01:04:25.230
slums, acting in this film gave them a chance

01:04:25.230 --> 01:04:29.490
for a new life. Director Danny Boyle arranged for them

01:04:29.490 --> 01:04:32.190
to be educated after the filming and made

01:04:32.190 --> 01:04:36.470
sure that they attended the Oscars in 2009, where the

01:04:36.470 --> 01:04:39.710
film won several awards, Chapter 12.

01:04:40.850 --> 01:04:41.870
India Today

01:04:43.370 --> 01:04:47.990
Jawaalal Nehru, India's first Prime Minister, had high hopes for

01:04:47.990 --> 01:04:48.550
his country.

01:04:49.470 --> 01:04:53.550
The night before India was declared a republic, Nehru expressed

01:04:53.550 --> 01:04:54.950
his feelings of triumph,

01:04:55.570 --> 01:04:58.870
but warned the Indian people that their new freedom was

01:04:58.870 --> 01:05:00.030
going to bring responsibility.

01:05:00.930 --> 01:05:04.290
He warned them not to rest in the future, but

01:05:04.290 --> 01:05:06.170
to keep trying to make things better.

01:05:07.070 --> 01:05:11.150
Today, India has the fastest growing economy in the world,

01:05:11.590 --> 01:05:14.030
and it is predicted that by 2050,

01:05:14.990 --> 01:05:19.090
it will have the second largest economy after China. The

01:05:19.090 --> 01:05:21.890
country is, indisputably, an emerging

01:05:21.890 --> 01:05:25.950
superpower, but the road to achieving Nehru's hopes for the

01:05:25.950 --> 01:05:27.010
future is long.

01:05:28.150 --> 01:05:32.470
Despite India's growing power, many obstacles still need to be

01:05:32.470 --> 01:05:33.030
dealt with.

01:05:33.870 --> 01:05:39.170
Poverty, lack of sanitation, road accidents, and pollution are everywhere.

01:05:40.290 --> 01:05:43.010
The government is taking measures to deal with these issues,

01:05:43.450 --> 01:05:44.890
and the progress is significant,

01:05:45.630 --> 01:05:47.370
but it isn't happening fast enough.

01:05:49.270 --> 01:05:50.090
The Obstacles

01:05:51.090 --> 01:05:57.370
India has the world's largest poor population. Between 1993 and

01:05:57.370 --> 01:06:00.450
2011, the number of poor people

01:06:00.450 --> 01:06:06.410
dropped 25%, but there are still around 270 million people

01:06:06.410 --> 01:06:08.330
living below the poverty line.

01:06:09.230 --> 01:06:12.690
Around 45% of these people can't read or write,

01:06:13.150 --> 01:06:15.710
which leads to poverty because they can't find

01:06:15.710 --> 01:06:22.190
jobs easily. The situation is improving though. Between 2001 and

01:06:22.190 --> 01:06:25.230
2011, the number of illiterate

01:06:25.230 --> 01:06:30.870
people was reduced by 31 million. With regard to sanitation,

01:06:31.850 --> 01:06:35.110
80% of the poor live in rural areas

01:06:35.110 --> 01:06:40.110
and have little access to basic services. Only 21%

01:06:40.110 --> 01:06:43.550
have proper toilets, 61% have electricity,

01:06:44.450 --> 01:06:49.390
and only 6% have access to tap water. As

01:06:49.390 --> 01:06:53.690
a result, sanitation is poor, and diseases spread easily

01:06:53.690 --> 01:06:57.830
and quickly. The good news is that things are changing.

01:06:58.710 --> 01:07:00.830
Today, the average life expectancy

01:07:01.230 --> 01:07:07.150
is 69, whereas in 1960, it was 41, so we

01:07:07.150 --> 01:07:09.550
can see that India has made a lot of progress

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:10.690
in this area.

01:07:11.590 --> 01:07:15.550
Another problem in India is the frequency of traffic accidents,

01:07:16.170 --> 01:07:17.410
which is amongst the highest

01:07:17.410 --> 01:07:22.590
in the world. According to a government agency report, more

01:07:22.590 --> 01:07:26.250
than 135,000 people in India die

01:07:26.250 --> 01:07:31.170
in traffic accidents every year. One cause of accidents is

01:07:31.170 --> 01:07:32.930
drivers speeding while talking

01:07:32.930 --> 01:07:37.290
on their mobile phones. A group of Indian researchers have

01:07:37.290 --> 01:07:39.050
developed a low-cost device

01:07:39.050 --> 01:07:43.450
which prevents drivers from receiving or making mobile phone calls

01:07:43.450 --> 01:07:44.170
while driving,

01:07:44.950 --> 01:07:49.810
but allows other passengers to call. Other causes of accidents

01:07:49.810 --> 01:07:51.370
are driving under the

01:07:51.370 --> 01:07:56.350
influence of alcohol, not using seatbelts and bike riders not

01:07:56.350 --> 01:07:59.330
using helmets. Overcrowded roads

01:07:59.330 --> 01:08:04.430
in bad condition don't help the situation either. A visit

01:08:04.430 --> 01:08:06.650
to Agra will confirm how

01:08:06.650 --> 01:08:11.670
serious India's air pollution problem is. The once-white marble

01:08:11.670 --> 01:08:13.370
exterior of the magnificent

01:08:13.370 --> 01:08:19.150
Taj Mahal is gradually turning yellow. In New Delhi, a

01:08:19.150 --> 01:08:21.030
15-metre high mountain of

01:08:21.030 --> 01:08:24.150
rubbish supports the claim that the capital is one of

01:08:24.150 --> 01:08:26.090
the world's most polluted cities.

01:08:27.090 --> 01:08:30.770
There aren't enough disposal areas for all of India's rubbish,

01:08:31.450 --> 01:08:32.670
and the few existing ones

01:08:32.670 --> 01:08:37.870
can't possibly hold anymore, so people burn waste outside their

01:08:37.870 --> 01:08:39.990
homes. This results in

01:08:39.990 --> 01:08:44.090
a blanket of smoke over many of India's villages, towns

01:08:44.090 --> 01:08:46.450
and cities. In addition,

01:08:46.950 --> 01:08:50.470
rubbish is thrown from passing trains, and the waste from

01:08:50.470 --> 01:08:52.070
train toilets is released

01:08:52.070 --> 01:08:57.590
directly onto the tracks. Rubbish is everywhere, even in the

01:08:57.590 --> 01:08:58.950
sacred Ganges River.

01:09:00.230 --> 01:09:04.690
How is the government dealing with this problem? Firstly, they

01:09:04.690 --> 01:09:06.830
are paying people to sort the rubbish

01:09:06.830 --> 01:09:12.970
into categories to be recycled, redistributed or disposed of. People

01:09:12.970 --> 01:09:14.850
receive a salary and keep

01:09:14.850 --> 01:09:17.950
any additional money made from selling the things they find

01:09:17.950 --> 01:09:20.930
in the rubbish. This new measure reduces

01:09:20.930 --> 01:09:27.230
the rubbish significantly, helping the environment and reducing poverty. Secondly,

01:09:27.710 --> 01:09:28.770
new rules for

01:09:28.770 --> 01:09:33.050
waste disposal were introduced in 2016 to help the problem,

01:09:33.690 --> 01:09:35.310
but they haven't been very effective

01:09:35.810 --> 01:09:37.310
because they aren't enforced.

01:09:38.950 --> 01:09:40.370
Cheap Labour in India

01:09:41.130 --> 01:09:44.970
Have you ever wondered why so many companies outsource their

01:09:44.970 --> 01:09:46.370
call centres to India?

01:09:47.250 --> 01:09:50.730
It's because India has a high number of English speakers

01:09:50.730 --> 01:09:53.350
who are ready to work hard for a low

01:09:53.350 --> 01:09:57.970
salary, but they don't only work in call centres. When

01:09:57.970 --> 01:10:00.510
you buy something on Amazon or book a

01:10:00.510 --> 01:10:04.050
ticket on Virgin, a lot of the computer processing work

01:10:04.050 --> 01:10:07.450
is done by people in India as this is more

01:10:07.450 --> 01:10:10.670
lucrative. Tomorrow's India

01:10:12.670 --> 01:10:18.590
By 2087, India will have the world's largest population. Today,

01:10:18.990 --> 01:10:20.470
half of this population consists

01:10:21.030 --> 01:10:24.870
of young people under the age of 25, many coming

01:10:24.870 --> 01:10:27.470
from underdeveloped places in the north of the

01:10:27.470 --> 01:10:33.850
country without education or qualifications. However, these are India's future

01:10:33.850 --> 01:10:34.430
leaders,

01:10:34.970 --> 01:10:37.210
so the government would like to alter the situation.

01:10:38.530 --> 01:10:42.850
They created a plan called Skill India, hoping to provide

01:10:42.850 --> 01:10:45.610
500 million people with skills

01:10:46.050 --> 01:10:52.470
by 2022, but this ambitious project met many obstacles and

01:10:52.470 --> 01:10:53.470
has now been abandoned.

01:10:54.550 --> 01:10:58.590
At the moment, it's impractical because so many people don't

01:10:58.590 --> 01:11:00.250
always have access to schools,

01:11:00.710 --> 01:11:05.130
banks and other services, but the digital age brings hope

01:11:05.130 --> 01:11:07.350
as more services and education

01:11:07.350 --> 01:11:11.670
are available online, so maybe things will improve in the

01:11:11.670 --> 01:11:12.010
future.

01:11:12.970 --> 01:11:17.630
Despite all these obstacles, India attracts larger numbers of tourists

01:11:17.630 --> 01:11:18.870
every year.

01:11:19.830 --> 01:11:23.650
It's difficult not to be captivated by India's spectacular landscapes

01:11:23.650 --> 01:11:24.790
and architecture,

01:11:25.550 --> 01:11:28.590
exotic cuisine and incredible spirituality.

01:11:42.010 --> 01:11:45.310
The English band, the Beatles, have in common with Mira

01:11:45.310 --> 01:11:48.290
Afasa, a French-born spiritual leader

01:11:48.290 --> 01:11:54.050
known as the Mother. Both imagined a world without any

01:11:54.050 --> 01:11:54.430
countries,

01:11:55.230 --> 01:11:59.350
nothing to kill or die for, no religion and people

01:11:59.350 --> 01:12:00.890
living life in peace.

01:12:02.190 --> 01:12:06.590
The Mother's vision led to the founding of Orville, City

01:12:06.590 --> 01:12:09.790
of Dawn, an experimental town

01:12:09.790 --> 01:12:12.110
in Tamil Nadu, India.

01:12:13.870 --> 01:12:20.090
Afasa founded Orville in 1968, transforming a useless piece of

01:12:20.090 --> 01:12:22.130
land into a green forest.

01:12:23.210 --> 01:12:28.310
Her dream was to promote human unity, practice sustainable living

01:12:28.310 --> 01:12:39.770
and provide for the future.

01:12:39.770 --> 01:12:44.430
A reality. Orville is trying to be a self-sufficient

01:12:44.430 --> 01:12:44.870
town.

01:12:45.690 --> 01:12:51.130
Farms produce organic food and energy systems generate solar, wind

01:12:51.130 --> 01:12:52.590
and gas energy.

01:12:54.090 --> 01:12:57.350
The people who live in Orville lead a unique lifestyle

01:12:57.350 --> 01:12:59.670
without politics or religion,

01:13:00.550 --> 01:13:05.130
which they believe can divide people. But not everything is

01:13:05.130 --> 01:13:06.210
perfect in Orville.

01:13:06.210 --> 01:13:10.450
The original idea was for the population to work for

01:13:10.450 --> 01:13:12.570
the community and for the community

01:13:12.570 --> 01:13:16.490
to take care of them. But this hasn't worked too

01:13:16.490 --> 01:13:16.810
well.

01:13:17.870 --> 01:13:23.270
Orvilleans need help from volunteers. Otherwise, they can't maintain the

01:13:23.270 --> 01:13:23.530
community.

01:13:24.650 --> 01:13:28.590
Although everybody receives basic health care and education,

01:13:29.590 --> 01:13:33.130
some people have found ways to make extra money and

01:13:33.130 --> 01:13:34.450
live a better lifestyle.

01:13:36.210 --> 01:13:40.350
Despite the problems, the dream is still alive to have

01:13:40.350 --> 01:13:40.730
a community

01:13:40.730 --> 01:13:45.250
that doesn't waste the Earth's resources and lives in peace

01:13:45.250 --> 01:13:46.070
and harmony.

01:13:47.330 --> 01:13:48.690
Would you like to live there?

01:13:49.090 --> 01:13:52.230
Page 80. Cross-curricular Focus.

01:13:53.310 --> 01:13:54.670
The Yoga Community

01:13:55.820 --> 01:13:59.970
From Hollywood film stars to the New Zealand rugby players,

01:13:59.970 --> 01:14:05.230
yoga is becoming more and more popular. In fact, in

01:14:05.230 --> 01:14:06.810
the USA, there are more

01:14:06.810 --> 01:14:12.130
yoga studios than Starbucks coffee shops. Today, people in the

01:14:12.130 --> 01:14:13.910
western world practice yoga to

01:14:13.910 --> 01:14:20.810
improve flexibility, alleviate stress and get physically fit. But 5

01:14:20.810 --> 01:14:21.830
,000 years ago,

01:14:22.170 --> 01:14:27.110
people from the Indus Sarasvati civilization practiced yoga for a

01:14:27.110 --> 01:14:28.050
different reason.

01:14:28.570 --> 01:14:33.610
To discover their true nature. To do this, people try

01:14:33.610 --> 01:14:34.970
to control their thoughts.

01:14:35.850 --> 01:14:39.390
We all think thoughts, and they control how we feel.

01:14:40.010 --> 01:14:42.770
They can make us feel happy or depressed.

01:14:43.750 --> 01:14:48.230
By practicing yoga, people focus on their thoughts for a

01:14:48.230 --> 01:14:51.230
long period of time and can begin to

01:14:51.230 --> 01:14:56.690
understand more about themselves. The special technique of controlling your

01:14:56.690 --> 01:14:57.890
thoughts is called

01:14:57.890 --> 01:15:05.230
meditation, and it existed as early as 1500 BC. In

01:15:05.230 --> 01:15:08.010
ancient times, people went to an ashram,

01:15:08.350 --> 01:15:12.510
meaning a shelter. In those days, the ashram was the

01:15:12.510 --> 01:15:15.750
house of the guru. A guru is a spiritual

01:15:15.750 --> 01:15:19.830
teacher who guides his or her disciples to a deeper

01:15:19.830 --> 01:15:21.170
understanding of themselves.

01:15:22.010 --> 01:15:25.890
In the past, children as young as 5 went to

01:15:25.890 --> 01:15:29.170
the guru's house to learn how to behave like Brahman,

01:15:29.490 --> 01:15:34.330
the one true God. Can you imagine leaving your parents

01:15:34.330 --> 01:15:35.510
at the age of 5?

01:15:36.570 --> 01:15:43.070
Very talented children graduated and received a Brahmana degree. In

01:15:43.070 --> 01:15:43.990
the course of time,

01:15:43.990 --> 01:15:47.950
these children became gurus and went on to teach others.

01:15:48.810 --> 01:15:51.130
But it was a very slow process,

01:15:51.950 --> 01:15:54.950
and often took more than 20 years.

